PriorityQueue in Java

PriorityQueue is a class in Java that implements the Queue interface.

Unlike a regular queue (FIFO), it processes elements based on priority, not order of insertion.

How it works

👉 Elements are ordered automatically:

smallest element first (by default)
uses natural ordering or a Comparator
Example idea
Add: 5 → 1 → 3  
Remove: 1 → 3 → 5

👉 Not FIFO — sorted order

Creating a PriorityQueue
import java.util.PriorityQueue;
import java.util.Queue;

Queue<Integer> queue = new PriorityQueue<>();
Adding Elements
queue.add(5);
queue.add(1);
queue.add(3);
Removing Elements
queue.poll(); // removes smallest element
Viewing Element
queue.peek(); // shows smallest element
Example
PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();

pq.add(5);
pq.add(1);
pq.add(3);

System.out.println(pq.poll()); // 1
System.out.println(pq.poll()); // 3
Custom Ordering (Comparator)
PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>(
    (a, b) -> b - a
);

👉 Now it works as max-heap (largest first)

Important Features
not FIFO
sorted by priority
allows duplicates
does NOT allow null ❌
not thread-safe
Internal Structure

👉 Based on a heap (binary heap)

root = highest priority element
efficient operations
Performance
Operation	Complexity
add()	O(log n)
poll()	O(log n)
peek()	O(1)
When to use PriorityQueue

Use it when:

you need priority-based processing
tasks have importance levels
scheduling systems
When NOT to use
when strict FIFO order needed → use Queue
when order must be stable → use other structures
Summary
PriorityQueue orders elements by priority
uses heap structure
fast and efficient
not based on insertion order
